---
import { ArrowLeft } from "@lucide/astro";
import Icon from "../../components/Icon.astro";
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const caseStudySchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "CreativeWork",
  name: "Invoice Management Redesign",
  description:
    "Redesigning invoice management into a clearer payment workflow for logistics finance teams at Container xChange.",
  author: {
    "@type": "Person",
    name: "Nikolaos Banis",
    url: "https://www.nikosbanis.com",
  },
  about: [
    "Invoice management",
    "Payment workflows",
    "Financial operations",
    "B2B SaaS",
  ],
  url: "https://www.nikosbanis.com/work/invoice-management",
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Invoice Management Redesign — Container xChange"
  description="Redesigning invoice and payment workflows for logistics finance teams, contributing to higher payment collections, fewer disputes, and faster invoice generation."
  canonicalPath="/work/invoice-management"
>
  <script
    slot="head"
    type="application/ld+json"
    is:inline
    set:html={JSON.stringify(caseStudySchema)}
  />

  <div class="site-frame case-frame">
    <div class="site-page">
      <div class="case-workspace">
        <div class="case-content">
          <nav class="cs-nav" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
            <a href="/" class="cs-back">
              <Icon icon={ArrowLeft} role="inline" />
              Nikolaos Banis
            </a>
          </nav>

          <article class="cs-article">
            <header class="cs-header">
          <div class="cs-kicker">
            <span class="meta">Container xChange</span>
            <span class="meta cs-kicker-sep" aria-hidden="true">·</span>
            <span class="meta">6-month project</span>
          </div>
          <h1>Invoice Management Redesign</h1>
          <p class="cs-subtitle">
            Turning invoice management into a clearer payment workflow
          </p>
          <p class="cs-introduction">
            Container xChange helps businesses lease, trade, and manage shipping
            containers. Invoicing was one of the areas where operational
            complexity showed up directly in the product.
          </p>
          <p class="cs-introduction">
            I was the sole designer across invoice creation, invoice lists,
            payment tracking, invoice details, filtering, dispute context,
            testing, and implementation support.
          </p>
            </header>

        <section class="cs-highlights" aria-labelledby="impact-title">
          <h2 class="cs-highlights-label" id="impact-title">Impact</h2>
          <dl class="cs-metrics">
            <div>
              <dt>Payment collections</dt>
              <dd>+24%</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Invoicing disputes</dt>
              <dd>−45%</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Dispute support requests</dt>
              <dd>−30%</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Invoice generation speed</dt>
              <dd>+38%</dd>
            </div>
            <div>
              <dt>Dispute resolution time</dt>
              <dd>5 → 3.2 days</dd>
            </div>
          </dl>
          <p class="cs-highlights-note meta">
            Informed by product analytics, support tickets, user interviews,
            four rounds of usability testing, and implementation constraints.
          </p>
        </section>

        <div class="cs-body">
          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>The problem was not only invoices</h2>
            <p>
              At first, invoice management looks simple. A user creates an
              invoice, sends it, tracks payment, and closes the loop when the
              money arrives. That works when the invoice is expected, correct,
              and easy to understand.
            </p>
            <p>
              At xChange, invoices often became exceptions. They could be
              overdue, disputed, tied to logistics activity the customer did
              not recognize, or blocked by missing context. When that happened,
              the invoice stopped being a document and became a question.
            </p>
            <ul class="cs-questions">
              <li>What is this charge for?</li>
              <li>Has it been paid?</li>
              <li>Why is it disputed?</li>
              <li>What needs to happen next?</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              The old experience did not answer those questions clearly enough.
              Users could access invoices, but unclear statuses, weak
              hierarchy, and limited filters made it difficult to understand
              what needed attention.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>Start with visibility</h2>
            <p>
              Finance teams do not manage invoices one by one. They scan for
              overdue payments, disputes, pending invoices, customer issues,
              and other exceptions.
            </p>
            <p>
              The previous interface required too much manual inspection before
              users could understand what was happening. The first design move
              was therefore to make invoice state clearer.
            </p>
            <p>
              Paid, pending, overdue, and disputed invoices became visible at a
              glance. The list view began helping users prioritize work rather
              than only displaying records, giving them a faster way to
              understand where money was stuck.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>Status does not explain the dispute</h2>
            <p>
              A disputed invoice is not resolved by labelling it “disputed.”
              The user still needs to understand why.
            </p>
            <p>
              In logistics, an invoice can be connected to container activity,
              transactions, routes, dates, charges, payment history, and
              customer agreements. When that context is difficult to find,
              users delay payment, open a dispute, or contact support.
            </p>
            <p>
              I redesigned the detail experience around the relationship
              between the invoice and its supporting transaction data. The goal
              was to explain what the invoice referred to, why the charge
              existed, and what action was required next.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>More detail created another problem</h2>
            <p>
              Adding context helped, but financial workflows need both detail
              and speed. Showing every piece of information with equal
              importance would make the screen technically complete but
              practically difficult to use.
            </p>
            <ol class="cs-sequence">
              <li>Show the invoice state</li>
              <li>Explain the reason</li>
              <li>Provide the supporting details</li>
              <li>Present the available action</li>
            </ol>
            <p>
              This hierarchy became the structure of the invoice detail page.
              Users did not need every detail immediately; they needed the right
              level of detail at the right moment.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>Finding invoices was part of the workflow</h2>
            <p>
              The old experience had almost no filtering. That was a major
              limitation because finance teams often work through groups of
              invoices rather than searching for one known record.
            </p>
            <ul class="cs-questions">
              <li>Overdue invoices</li>
              <li>Disputed invoices</li>
              <li>Invoices from a specific customer</li>
              <li>Invoices that need action this week</li>
              <li>Invoices connected to a specific transaction</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              I added advanced filters and search patterns around the way
              finance teams investigate payment issues. This changed the list
              from a table of records into an operational workspace.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>Backend limitations shaped the solution</h2>
            <p>
              Not every piece of invoice logic was easy to expose, combine, or
              filter. Some desired states and relationships depended on backend
              structures that were not designed for this level of workflow
              visibility.
            </p>
            <p>
              I worked closely with product and engineering to identify which
              states were reliable, which filters were feasible, and where the
              interface needed to account for technical limits.
            </p>
            <p>
              Some ideas were simplified and others sequenced for later. The
              priority was preserving user value without designing flows the
              system could not support reliably.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>Testing the workflow</h2>
            <p>
              We tested the redesign through four rounds of usability testing.
              The purpose was not only to confirm that the screens looked
              clearer, but to determine whether users could complete the
              payment workflow with less confusion.
            </p>
            <ul class="cs-questions">
              <li>Can users find the invoice they need?</li>
              <li>Can they understand its status?</li>
              <li>Can they see why it is overdue or disputed?</li>
              <li>Can they identify the next action?</li>
              <li>Can they do this without contacting support?</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              Feedback refined the hierarchy, filters, transaction context, and
              invoice creation flow.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>Reducing friction at the start</h2>
            <p>
              Some invoice problems began before payment. The creation flow
              required too much manual input, increasing the chance of mistakes
              and slowing users down.
            </p>
            <p>
              I reduced manual fields and simplified the flow. Invoice
              generation time fell from three minutes to 1.8 minutes, reducing
              friction before an invoice was sent.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="cs-section">
            <h2>The final shift</h2>
            <p>
              The redesign changed the product from a place where users could
              access invoices into a workflow for managing payment issues.
            </p>
            <ul class="cs-outcomes">
              <li>Users could find invoices faster</li>
              <li>Invoice state became easier to understand</li>
              <li>Dispute context stayed connected to its transaction data</li>
              <li>Next actions became clearer</li>
              <li>Invoice creation required less manual effort</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              For the business, this translated into higher payment collection,
              fewer disputes, and fewer support requests. For users, the value
              was simpler: they no longer had to piece together the story of an
              invoice themselves.
            </p>
          </section>
        </div>
          </article>
        </div>
        <aside class="case-empty" aria-hidden="true"></aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
